        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "B−1 Show that the curve x3 + 3xy + y3 = 1 contains only one set of three distinct points, A, B, and C, which are ver- tices of an equilateral triangle, and find its area.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5231372549019608,
          0.13454545454545455,
          0.9184313725490196,
          0.17939393939393938
        ],
        "order": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2006_Problems_2006_page_001_1",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "A−1 Find the volume of the region of points (x, y, z) such that",
        "bbox": [
          0.09254901960784313,
          0.13515151515151516,
          0.4894117647058824,
          0.1509090909090909
        ],
        "order": 3
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2006_Problems_2006_page_001_11",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "B−2 Prove that, for every set X = {x1, x2, . . , xn} of n real numbers, there exists a non-empty subset S of X and an integer m such that",
        "bbox": [
          0.523921568627451,
          0.18848484848484848,
          0.9192156862745098,
          0.23212121212121212
        ],
        "order": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2006_Problems_2006_page_001_2",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "A–2 Alice and Bob play a game in which they take turns removing stones from a heap that initially has n stones. The number of stones removed at each turn must be one less than a prime number. The winner is the player who takes the last stone. Alice plays first. Prove that there are infinitely many n such that Bob has a winning strat- egy. (For example, if n = 17, then Alice might take 6 leaving 11; then Bob might take 1 leaving 10; then Al- ice can take the remaining stones to win.)",
        "bbox": [
          0.09333333333333334,
          0.19515151515151516,
          0.49019607843137253,
          0.32666666666666666
        ],
        "order": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2006_Problems_2006_page_001_12",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "B—3 Let S be a finite set of points in the plane. A linear parti- tion of S is an unordered pair {A, B} of subsets of S such that A U B = S, A ∩ B = 0, and A and B lie on opposite sides of some straight line disjoint from S (A or B may be empty). Let Ls be the number of linear partitions of S. For each positive integer n, find the maximum of Ls over all sets S of n points.",
        "bbox": [
          0.523921568627451,
          0.2824242424242424,
          0.9192156862745098,
          0.38303030303030305
        ],
        "order": 6
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2006_Problems_2006_page_001_3",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "A—3 Let 1, 2, 3, ... , 2005, 2006, 2007, 2009, 2012, 2016, ... be a sequence defined by xk = k for k = 1, 2, . ., 2006 and xk+1 = xk + xk−2005 for k ≥ 2006. Show that the sequence has 2005 consecutive terms each divisible by 2006.",
        "bbox": [
          0.09333333333333334,
          0.33575757575757575,
          0.4894117647058824,
          0.4078787878787879
        ],
        "order": 7
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2006_Problems_2006_page_001_13",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "B–4 Let Z denote the set of points in R\" whose coordinates are 0 or 1. (Thus Z has 2n elements, which are the ver- tices of a unit hypercube in IRn.) Given a vector sub- space V of Rn, let Z(V) denote the number of members of Z that lie in V. Let k be given, 0 ≤ k ≤ n. Find the maximum, over all vector subspaces V ⊆ Rn of dimen- sion k, of the number of points in V ∩Z. [Editorial note: the proposers probably intended to write Z(V) instead of \"the number of points in V ∩ Z\", but this changes nothing.]",
        "bbox": [
          0.5247058823529411,
          0.39212121212121215,
          0.9192156862745098,
          0.5381818181818182
        ],
        "order": 8
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2006_Problems_2006_page_001_4",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "A−4 Let S = {1, 2, . ., n} for some integer n > 1. ay a per- mutation π of S has a local maximum at k ∈ S if",
        "bbox": [
          0.09333333333333334,
          0.41818181818181815,
          0.49019607843137253,
          0.4478787878787879
        ],
        "order": 9
      }
    ]
  },
